      { tradition: "atta_veerattanam", story: "Korukkai is the KAMA DAHANA shrine of the eight Atta Veerattanam temples — the place where Shiva opened his third eye and reduced Kamadeva (Manmatha), god of desire, to ashes when Kama tried to break his meditation. Shiva is Kama Dahana Murti / Kama-Anga-Nasan; the nearby Vibhuti Kuttai preserves Kama's ashes. Pilgrims come to conquer desire and ego. Kama was later restored only to his widow Rati (at nearby Ponnur), remaining formless (ananga) to all others." },
      { tradition: "other", story: "The temple's name traces to the sage Theerthavahu (Kurungai Munivar), whose shortened hands were restored by Shiva after he brought Ganga water for the Soola Theertham; Kurungai became Korukkai. Vishnu, Lakshmi, Brahma, and Muruga are said to have worshipped here. A 9th-century Chola foundation with Nayaka additions, administered by the Dharmapuram Aadheenam." }
